<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
This is a holothurian. The stout cylindrical processes forming a 'complete closed circle'from the original description are actually tentacles surrounding the mouth. Each tentacle is short and branched, but each branch is like a wart, making them apparently crenulated. The long, typical reddish brown chaetae found pen 
<pageBreakToken pageId="10" pageNumber="11" start="start">etrating</pageBreakToken>
the body belong to other, deep-water polychaetes, such as the aphroditid 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Aphroditidae" genus="Laetmonice" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Laetmonice" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Laetmonice</taxonomicName>
, which during dredging, frequently loose their chaetae. The holothurians belongs in the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Oligotrichea" family="Halteriidae" genus="Meseres" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Chromista" lsidName="Meseres" order="Halteriida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="genus">Meseres</taxonomicName>
, currently in the family 
<taxonomicName family="Synallactidae" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="family">Synallactidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="O'Loughlin, PM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of Museum Victoria" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="147 - 179" title="A review of pygal-furrowed Synallactidae (Echinodermata: Holothuroidea), with new species from the Antarctic, Atlantic and Pacific Oceans." volume="62" year="2005">
<normalizedToken originalValue="O’Loughlin">O'Loughlin</normalizedToken>
and Ahearn 2005
</bibRefCitation>
); after 
<bibRefCitation author="O'Loughlin, PM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of Museum Victoria" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="297 - 325" title="Report on selected species of BANZARE and ANARE Holothuroidea, with reviews of Meseres Ludwig and Heterocucumis Panning (Echinodermata)." volume="59" year="2002">
<normalizedToken originalValue="O’Loughlin">O'Loughlin</normalizedToken>
(2002)
</bibRefCitation>
, two species have been described from the same region: 
<taxonomicName class="Oligotrichea" family="Halteriidae" genus="Meseres" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Chromista" lsidName="Meseres torvus" order="Halteriida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="torvus">Meseres torvus</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Théel">Theel</normalizedToken>
, 1886) and 
<taxonomicName class="Oligotrichea" family="Halteriidae" genus="Meseres" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Chromista" lsidName="Meseres macdonaldi" order="Halteriida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="macdonaldi">Meseres macdonaldi</taxonomicName>
Ludwig, 1894; however, the former species has an uncertain generic placement, whereas the second is retained in its genus (
<bibRefCitation author="O'Loughlin, PM" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of Museum Victoria" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="147 - 179" title="A review of pygal-furrowed Synallactidae (Echinodermata: Holothuroidea), with new species from the Antarctic, Atlantic and Pacific Oceans." volume="62" year="2005">
<normalizedToken originalValue="O’Loughlin">O'Loughlin</normalizedToken>
and Ahearn 2005
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
